    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Another cause for uncertainty is the fact that Bird Shoal is not a natural formation, but an almost entirely man-made island—the result of large-scale spoil dredging efforts off Beaufort’s coast to facilitate ship traffic, Newton explained.</p>
<p>In an effort to allow larger vessels to pass the town on their way to port, Beaufort years ago dug up hundreds of tons of seabed sand and deposited it by the nearby Rachel Carson Nation Wildlife Refuge. As a result, the town inadvertently destroyed a thick wall of marshland that had protected it from the Atlantic Ocean, replacing it with the thin wedge of sand known today as Bird Shoal. An artificial barrier island like this has never been thoroughly studied before, Newton explained.</p>
<p>Even so, he said he still believes there is hope for Beaufort.&nbsp;</p>
<p>“We’re still at the recognition stage right now,” he said. “At some point you have to recognize the issue at hand, and then start to work on a remedy.”</p>

